Types of OOP's

Encapsulation:

Encapsulation mean is wrapping up of data & member functions in a single unit called class. typically it's purpose is to 
protect data by data hiding techniques that restrict directly access of data to main function or program.

Difference between a class and Encapsulation:
Think class as a container and Encapsulation as a technique/method to protect the container.
Class is a blue print or template use to create objects while Encapsulation is a process of hiding internal data and restricting access.

Class collects methods and data together in one place while Encapsulation protect that data within that collection.

Class is a physical structure of a code while Encapsulation is a concept or principle of oop.


